<h3>
    <strong>1. Siuslaw River (Hwy 36 Corridor &amp; Mainstem)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Distance:</strong> ~40 miles west of Eugene (toward Florence) 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Species &amp; Timing:</strong> Fall Chinook and Coho runs from <strong>September through October</strong>, with steelhead in winter/early spring 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Access &amp; Tactics:</strong> Drift boats around Cushman and Mapleton; use trollers/drift methods with plugs, spinners, or roe. Falls offer steelhead opportunities late season
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>2. Umpqua River</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Distance:</strong> ~90 miles south, near Roseburg &amp; Reedsport 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Species &amp; Timing:</strong>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <strong>Spring Chinook:</strong> March–June, best April–early June
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Fall Chinook &amp; Coho:</strong> September–November 
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Top Spots:</strong> Estuary &amp; Winchester Bay (trolling), Scottsburg &amp; Main Umpqua (back-bouncing roe, plugs), North Umpqua for drift and fly fishing&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>3. Willamette River (Eugene–Springfield Stretch)</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Distance:</strong> 0–15 miles north of Eugene 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Species &amp; Timing:</strong> Spring Chinook (May–June) and Coho (Sept–Oct) 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Access &amp; Methods:</strong> Bank and boat access at Alton Baker, Island Park, Beltline area; use trolling, float rigs, and spinners near confluence of McKenzie &amp; Coast Fork&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>4. McKenzie River</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Distance:</strong> 10–20 miles east 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Species &amp; Timing:</strong> Wild rainbows year-round, plus spring Chinook &amp; summer steelhead in late spring/early summer 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Access &amp; Tactics:</strong> Fish near Leaburg and Dexter dams—float and drift for Chinook; trout fly fishing in the lower river near Springfield&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>5. North Santiam / South Santiam Rivers</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Distance:</strong> 40–60 miles northeast (North Santiam) / east (South Santiam) 
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Species &amp; Timing:</strong> Spring Chinook (North Santiam May–June), Coho in early fall (South Santiam Sept–Oct)
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Access &amp; Methods:</strong> Float or drift fish from public access; use roe drift rigs, plugs, and spinners near spawning grounds&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    <strong>6. Siuslaw River’s North Fork &amp; Lake Creek</strong>
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Distance:</strong> ~40 mi west via Hwy 126
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Species &amp; Timing:</strong> Fall Chinook &amp; Coho in tributaries like Lake Creek after rain; steelhead winter/early spring
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Access &amp; Tactics:</strong> Drift boats from Whittaker Creek launches; back-trolling Hot-Shots, spinners&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
